At the time of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], according to the [[Office for National Statistics]], the Urban Sub-division of Eccles was part of the [[Greater Manchester Urban Area]] and had a total resident population of 36,610, of which 17,924 (48.96%) were male and 18,686 (51.04%) were female.  The settlement occupied 812 hectares, compared with 783 in the 1991 census.  Its population density was 45.09 people per hectare compared with an average of 40.20 across the Greater Manchester Urban Area.<ref name="2001urbanarea">{{Citation |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8272&More=Y |title=KS01 Usual resident population: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>  The median age of the population is 37, compared with 36 within the Greater Manchester Urban Area and 37 across England and Wales.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&Pos=2&ColRank=1&Rank=224 |title=KS02 Age Structure: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>

The majority of the population of Eccles was born in England (91.94%); 2.61% were born elsewhere within the United Kingdom, 0.70% within the rest of the European Union, and 2.99% elsewhere in the world.<ref name="2001birthdata">{{Citation |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8279&More=Y |title=KS05 Country of Birth: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>

Data on religious beliefs across the town in the 2001 census show that 77.07% declared themselves to be [[Christian]], 12.05% said they held no religion, and 2.26% reported themselves as [[Muslim]].<ref name="2001religiondata">{{Citation |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8286&More=Y |title=KS07 Religion: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>

Eccles is within the [[Manchester]] [[Larger Urban Zone]],<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/economic_unit/docs/wp13_towards_a_common_standard.pdf|title=Towards a Common Standard|page=29|format=PDF|publisher=Greater London Authority|accessdate=2008-10-05}}</ref> and the Manchester [[Travel to Work Area]].<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/geography/ttwa.asp |title=Travel to Work Areas |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=2008-09-24}}</ref>

===By ward===
The Eccles area consists of the [[Wards of the United Kingdom|wards]] of Barton, [[Winton, Greater Manchester|Winton]], and Eccles.<ref name="Salfordcouncileccles" />

[[File:Eccles shopping centre.png|left|thumb|Eccles shopping centre]]
According to the [[Office for National Statistics]], at the time of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], the ward of Eccles had a population of 11,413, of which 5,546 were male, and 5,867 female.<ref name="populationeccles">{{Citation | title = Eccles (ward) - 2001 Census Area Statistics | publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6097391&c=eccles&d=14&e=16&g=353750&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1234520777242&enc=1 | accessdate = 2009-02-13}}</ref>  The ward of Winton had a population of 12,752,<ref name="populationwinton">{{Citation | title = Winton (ward) - 2001 Census Area Statistics | publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6103255&c=winton&d=14&e=16&g=354246&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1234550060562&enc=1 | accessdate = 2009-02-13}}</ref> and the ward of [[Barton-upon-Irwell|Barton]] had a population of 10,434,<ref name="populationbarton">{{Citation | title = Barton (ward) - 2001 Census Area Statistics | publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6095089&c=barton&d=14&e=16&g=353579&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1234550226000&enc=1 | accessdate = 2009-02-13}}</ref> giving the larger administrative area of Eccles a total population of 34,599.

Eccles is the ninth most densely populated ward in Salford, and has the highest number and proportion of people aged 75&nbsp;and over of all wards in Salford.  Levels of crime are below the average for the city.  The adult population tends to be more qualified than the city average, and primary and secondary education results are also slightly higher than average for Salford.  Unemployment is below average, with people tending to work longer hours.  More residents live in purpose-built and converted flats than do in the city as a whole, with a minority occupying [[Single-family detached home|detached]] houses or [[bungalow]]s.  Between 1994&nbsp;and&nbsp;2004,  367&nbsp;homes were added to the ward, above the average for Salford.<ref name="Eccleswardprofile">{{Citation | title = City of Salford: Eccles ward profile | url = http://www.salford.gov.uk/living/planning/planning-research/salfordwardprofiles.htm | publisher = Salford City Council | year = 2004 | accessdate = 2009-02-15 }}</ref>

[[File:Terraced housing and tower blocks eccles greater manchester.png|right|thumb|Tower blocks dominate the landscape of Eccles, forming a stark contrast with Victorian brick terraced housing.<ref>{{Citation | title = 1890 - LANCASHIRE AND FURNESS 1:2,500 | url = http://www.old-maps.co.uk/indexmappage2.aspx?action=forcexy&easting=378100&northing=398700 | publisher = old-maps.co.uk | year = 1890 | accessdate = 2009-02-16 }}</ref>]]
Neighbouring Winton is the sixth most densely populated ward in the region and in 2001 had proportionally more children than the city as a whole.  Crime is generally below average, with falling rates of burglary in 2005.  Education standards for both adults and children are below city average with minor improvements to [[GCSE]] results between 2005 and 2006.  Unemployment is higher than average for Salford, with areas of severe income deprivation both to the north and south of the ward.  Residents are on average more likely to live in [[semi-detached]] housing, with 208&nbsp;homes added between 1994&nbsp;and&nbsp;2004.<ref name="Wintonwardprofile">{{Citation | title = City of Salford: Winton ward profile | url = http://www.salford.gov.uk/living/planning/planning-research/salfordwardprofiles.htm | publisher = Salford City Council | year = 2004 | accessdate = 2009-02-15 }}</ref>

To the south, the ward of Barton is the third most densely populated in Salford with little population change between 1991&nbsp;and&nbsp;2001.  It has proportionally more over-85 year olds than the city as a whole, with low adult and primary school education standards, but significant improvements in GCSE results of late.  Some parts of Barton are amongst the worst&nbsp;20% of areas in the country for child poverty, with below city-average childcare provision.  Unemployment is higher than average for Salford.  Almost half the homes in the ward are [[Terraced house|terraced]] housing, with an extra 300 properties built between 1994&nbsp;and&nbsp;2004.<ref name="Bartonwardprofile">{{Citation | title = City of Salford: Barton ward profile | url = http://www.salford.gov.uk/living/planning/planning-research/salfordwardprofiles.htm | publisher = Salford City Council | year = 2004 | accessdate = 2009-02-15 }}</ref>

==Economy==
To the east of the town centre, the West One [[retail park]] was opened in November 2001 at a cost of <U+00A3>53M.  It is in competition with the nearby [[Trafford Centre]] and [[Salford Quays|Lowry Outlet Mall]], and as a result has suffered a loss of trade.  A [[Morrisons]] supermarket is just outside the town centre,<ref>{{Citation | title = Welcome to Morrisons Supermarkets, Eccles  | url = http://www.morrisons.co.uk/Store-finder/Store-Details/?type=qs&value=M5&recordid=1&lat=53.48249&lon=-2.33508 | publisher = morrisons.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-02-25}}</ref> and 400&nbsp;jobs may be created if a planned new [[Tesco]] store opens.<ref>{{Citation | title = New Tesco to create 400 jobs | url = http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/s/1092381_new_tesco_to_create_400_jobs | last = Keeling | first = Neal | date = 2009-01-23 | publisher = manchestereveningnews.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-02-16 }}</ref>

Until shortly after its closure was announced on 9 May 2006, the [[Great Universal Stores]] group used the former Eccles Spinning and Manufacturing Company building in Winton.  Operations have since been transferred to a site in [[Shaw and Crompton]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Littlewoods axe 1,200 in shake-up | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4754841.stm | publisher = news.bbc.co.uk | date = 2006-05-09 | accessdate = 2009-02-24}}</ref><ref name="GUSwarehouse"/>  The town still has a manufacturing industry.  Americhem Europe manufactures colouring for plastics and nylon fibres, employing 75 staff with a turnover of <U+00A3>10M.<ref>{{Citation | title = Eccles plastics expansion | last = Rooth | first = Ben | url = http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/business/s/1042196_eccles_plastics_expansion | publisher = manchestereveningnews.co.uk | date = 2008-03-25 | accessdate = 2009-02-16 }}</ref>  The Eccles-based insurance broker and financial services specialist CBG Group which worldwide employs 180&nbsp;people, has its head office near the town centre.<ref>{{Citation | title = CBG Group raises <U+00A3>1.65m | url = http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/business/s/1078405_cbg_group_raises_165m | date = 2008-11-07 | publisher = manchestereveningnews.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-02-16 }}</ref>  The employment agency Morsons is also based in the town and supplies thousands of employees to various hi-tech employers.<ref>{{Citation | title = Morson's jobs boom | url = http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/business/s/1067223_morsons_jobs_boom | last = Feddy | first = Kevin | date = 2008-09-18 | publisher = manchestereveningnews.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-02-16 }}</ref>

